Here it is. Complete. From power button to your program running.

---

**The whole picture — from power button to your program running**

---

## The moment you press power

You press the power button.

Electricity flows to the motherboard. The motherboard wakes up the CPU. The CPU immediately starts fetch-decode-execute — but RAM is empty. Nothing loaded yet. So where does it fetch from?

There's a tiny chip soldered directly onto the motherboard called the **BIOS** — Basic Input Output System. It has the very first instructions hardcoded into it permanently. Even with no OS, no SSD, nothing — these instructions exist.

BIOS wakes up and does one job — **POST**. Power On Self Test. It checks that everything exists and works. Is RAM there? Is the CPU responding? Is there a keyboard? Is there a storage device?

If everything checks out — BIOS looks for an OS. It checks the SSD, finds a small program called the **bootloader** sitting at the very beginning of the drive. Loads that bootloader into RAM. Hands control to it.

The bootloader's only job is to find the OS on the SSD and load it into RAM.

Now the OS is in RAM. Running. Alive.

---

## What the OS actually is

The OS is not one program. It's thousands of programs working together — all loaded into RAM — all running simultaneously — managing every single resource on your machine.

It manages —

**Memory** — decides which program gets which part of RAM. Makes sure programs don't accidentally read each other's memory.

**CPU time** — your CPU can only do one thing at a time. The OS slices time into tiny pieces and gives each running program a slice. So fast it feels like everything runs simultaneously. It doesn't. The OS is juggling.

**Storage** — manages reading and writing to SSD. When you save a file the OS decides where on the SSD it goes. When you open a file the OS finds it and loads it.

**Hardware** — keyboard, mouse, screen, speakers. Every device has a **driver** — a small program that knows how to talk to that specific hardware. The OS loads those drivers and routes everything through them.

The OS never stops. It runs from the moment you power on until the moment you power off. Everything you do — every click, every keypress, every program you open — goes through the OS first.

---

## What's sitting on your SSD

Three kinds of files relevant to your code —

**Header files** — plain text files. Just descriptions. "printf exists and looks like this." Nothing executable. No actual code. Just information telling the compiler what functions exist and what they look like.

**Library files** — binary files. Actual compiled code. The real printf. The real cout. Everything pre-compiled by someone else and sitting on your SSD waiting to be used.

**Your source code** — plain text. What you wrote. Completely meaningless to the CPU yet. Just characters in a file.

---

## The professor analogy

Header files = table of contents of a textbook. Tells you what exists and what it looks like.

Library files = the actual textbook. The real knowledge. The real compiled code.

The professors wrote the textbooks once. Published them. They sit on the SSD shelf forever. Every programmer in the world borrows from the same shelf.

---

## When you click compile — who touches what

Four players run one after another. Each one does its job and hands the result to the next.

---

**Preprocessor** — touches your source file and the header files.

Reads your text file top to bottom. Finds every line starting with `#`. Handles it.

Sees `#include <iostream>` — goes to the system folder on SSD, opens the iostream header file, copy pastes its entire contents into your code at that exact spot. Your file is now much bigger than you wrote.

Sees `#define PI 3.14` — goes through your entire file and replaces every occurrence of PI with 3.14. Mechanical find and replace.

Done. Hands the expanded text to the compiler. Disappears. The compiler never even knows the preprocessor existed.

---

**Compiler** — touches only your expanded source text.

Reads it like reading a sentence. Breaks it into tokens — `int`, `main`, `(`, `)`, `{`, `return`, `0`, `}`. Like identifying individual words.

Checks grammar — is this valid C++? If you wrote `itn` instead of `int` — it doesn't recognise that token. Cannot continue. Error.

If no errors — builds a logical tree of what your code means. Then converts that into assembly code. Then binary. Produces an **object file**.

But your object file has gaps. Everywhere you used `cout` or `printf` — the compiler left a note. "I need the actual code for this function. Someone bring it."

---

**Assembler** — in modern compilers this is built into the compiler itself.

Converts assembly instructions into binary machine code. MOV becomes a specific pattern of 1s and 0s. ADD becomes another pattern. The CPU will physically respond to these patterns.

---

**Linker** — touches your object file and the library files on SSD.

Reads the notes the compiler left. Opens the relevant library files. Finds the actual binary code for cout, printf, every function you used. Stitches them into your object file. Fills every gap.

If your program has multiple .cpp files — joins all their object files together into one.

Result — one complete executable file. No gaps. No missing pieces. Pure binary. Ready.

---

## When you run the program

You double click the executable or type `./program` in terminal.

The OS picks it up. Loads it from SSD into RAM. Finds your `main()` function — the agreed starting point between every C++ program and every OS. Points the CPU's instruction pointer at it.

CPU starts fetch-decode-execute on your binary. One instruction at a time. Billions of times per second.

Your program runs.

---

## The complete chain

```
Power button pressed
      ↓
BIOS wakes up — checks hardware — POST
      ↓
Bootloader loads OS into RAM
      ↓
OS runs — manages everything forever
      ↓
You write source code — plain text on SSD
      ↓
Click compile
      ↓
Preprocessor — pastes headers, 
               find replaces, expands file
      ↓
Compiler — checks grammar, builds logic tree,
           produces object file with gaps
      ↓
Linker — fills gaps from library files,
         produces complete executable
      ↓
You run the executable
      ↓
OS loads it into RAM
      ↓
CPU executes binary from main() onwards
      ↓
Your program runs
```

---

From sand to switch to BIOS to OS to compiler to your program running.

One chain. No magic anywhere in it.

